ce:section.ce:para:
The analytical ability of the aptasensor based on p-L-Glu and peptides was explored, and the results are shown in Fig. 4
                        . As can be seen from Fig. 4, when the ATP concentration was from 0.01 pM to 1.0 μM, the current response of the aptasensor showed a good linear relationship (R2 = 0.998), and the linear equation is ΔI = 4.94215LogC + 75.16074. Thus, the linear detection range of the aptasensor is 0.01 pM-1.0 μM, the limit of detection (LOD) is 0.01 pM (S/N = 3). The excellent performance of the aptasensor was mainly attributed to the following aspects. Firstly, p-L-Glu was directly modified on the electrode surface by electrodeposition method, which enhanced the bonding strength between the p-L-Glu and GCE. Secondly, p-L-Glu belongs to biological material. When it was deposited on the electrode surface, it can improve the biocompatibility of the aptasensor. Moreover, p-L-Glu has lots of carboxyl groups, which not only provided more bonding sites for aptATP fixation, but also can enhance the hydrophilicity of the electrode interface to improve the antifouling ability. Finally, the peptides as antifouling materials can block unbound sites on the surface of the aptasensor, and also can reduce the non-specific adsorption of the sensor surface. In addition, the strong affinity between aptATP and ATP is also an important factor in improving sensor performance. In a word, the aptasensor prepared in this study exhibited excellent performance for detecting ATP compared with the reported works (Table 1
                        ).
